Introduction

			    License Introduction


    Some processes on the computer require special capabilities to perform
    their tasks properly.  Other processes require access to information and
    functionality.  License is the mechanism used to control the access each
    individual or program may obtain to these capabilities and information.

    License is set using the OPER program, which reads a secure system data
    structure and verifies access to any given license via password controls.

    Once license is set, the user may manipulate active license using the
    monitor commands ENABLE and DISABLE.  These commands allow a user to set
    license using OPER and enable or disable various licenses individually.

    The "SETE 0" monitor command is used to disable license completely until
    it is set again using the OPER program.

    License is administered by the systems staff and the validations groups
    within McDonnell Douglas ISC.  Please check with your management in order
    to determine whether you are required to perform tasks on the PDP-10s
    which require license.  License will ONLY be granted where it is needed.
    (Note:  If your managment doesn't have a good reason why you require a
    specific license, you probably don't really need it.)

    The SETOP program is used to administer licenses and OPER names which are
    authorized to use them.  The OPPS program is a mini-SETOP which allows a
    user or manager to change the password associated with their OPER names
    or their subordinates without having to bother with additional commands in
    the SETOP program.

    The validations group is currently responsible for the verification of
    employee status and the creation and deletion of OPER names.  Managers
    and individuals with the license-granting capability are responsible for
    administering license to each individual.  Thus, DO NOT ask validations
    to give you license.  The validations group ONLY gives you a valid OPER
    name.  Your manager, co-workers or system support staff administer the
    specific licenses granted to your OPER name.

    Managers and individual employees that have OPER names should be familiar
    with the PDP-10 commands and the programs used to administer license in
    order to better utilize and understand the responsibility that comes with
    having an OPER name.


